1. What is RDP Short path? Explain its types.
RDP Short Path: RDP Short Path establishes a UDP-based transport set up a local device,
Windows app and
session host in AVD. By default RDP begins a TCP-based reverse connect transport, then tries
to establish a
remote session using UDP. If the UDP connection succeeds, the TCP connection drops,
otherwise TCP
connection is used as a fallback connection mechanism.
RDP short path allows you to establish connection between client machine and session host
directly over
UDP port and it uses multiple ways to establish a connectivity directly between the client
machine and
session host as below:
By default UDP Port 3390 is used and it can be changed to use a different port.
RDP Short Path can be used in two ways:
Managed Networks - Where direct connectivity is established between the client and the
session host when
using a private connection, such as a site to site virtual private network (VPN). A connection
using a managed
network is established in one of the following ways:
1. A direct UDP connection between the client device and session host, where you need to
enable the
RDP Short path listener and allow an inbound port on each session host to accept
connections.
2. A direct UDP connection between the client device and session host, using the Simple
Traversal
Underneath NAT (STUN) protocol between a client and session host. Inbound ports on the
session
host are not required to be allowed.
Public networks - where direct connectivity is established between the client and the session
host when
using a public connection. There are two connection types when using a public connection,
which are listed
here in order of preference:
1. A direct UDP connection using the Simple Traversal Underneath NAT (STUN) protocol
between a
client and session host.
2. An relayed UDP connection using the Traversal Using Relay NAT (TURN) protocol between
a client
and session host.
2. Mention the key benefits of RDP Shortpath
RDP Short path enhances Azure Virtual Desktop performance and reliability by enabling a
direct, UDP-based
connection between the client and session host.
RDP Short path reduces the latency and improves the user experience as the low RTT will be
there as the
connection is directly made between client and session host.
Using URCP to enhance UDP achieves the best performance by dynamically learning
network parameters
and providing the protocol with a rate control mechanism.
Higher throughput.
When using STUN, the removal of extra relay points reduces round-trip time improves
connection reliability
and the user experience with latency-sensitive applications and input methods.
RDP Short path brings support for configuring Quality of Service priority for RDP connections
through
Differentiated Services Code Point marks.
The RDP Short path transport allows limiting outbound network traffic by specifying a
throttle rate for each
session.
